          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821598?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1976 年，托尼·贝内特 (Tony Bennett) 在伦敦 Palladium 剧院</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·雷德芬/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周五去世，享年 96 岁的托尼·贝内特 (Tony Bennett) 从来不喜欢被称为流行歌手。相反，他认为自己是“美国歌曲集的爵士乐诠释者”。他对摇滚乐的蔑视有时阻碍了他的职业生涯，尤其是在 20 世纪 60 年代末和 70 年代，当时他正处于谷底。但在 1986 年，60 岁的贝内特先生发起了音乐史上最引人注目、最持久的后期复出之一。</p><p>在他七十年的职业生涯中，贝内特先生的声音充满了歌剧般的乐观主义的阳光。他发行了100多张专辑和80多首单曲，获得19项格莱美奖（其中17项是1990年以后）并获得格莱美终身成就奖。从 1951 年他的第一张冠军单曲《Because of You》到 2021 年他与 Lady Gaga 合作的第二张专辑《Love for Sale》，Bennett 先生的声音风格通常会带来胜利的结局，此时他的力量和即兴技巧结合在一起，达到令人愉悦的渐强。</p><p>贝内特先生从未动摇过他爵士乐、健谈的街头歌手风格，即使在 1986 年回到哥伦比亚并发行了《The Art of Excellence》之后也是如此。随后该厂牌推出了一长串专辑，到 2010 年代，Bennett 先生已成为仍在工作的最年长的前摇滚明星，并成为年轻听众的父亲形象，这在很大程度上要归功于他与 Lady Gaga 的合作。</p><p>两人于 2014 年发行了《Cheek to Cheek》，该专辑赢得了格莱美奖，并进行了电视特别节目和全球巡演。虽然这次合并给 Lady Gaga 带来了老派的声望和一位传奇导师，但贝内特先生最终得到了更好的交易。 Gaga 台上台下的溺爱和女儿般的赞美使他再次成为超级巨星。</p><p> 2014 年，当我为《华尔街日报》采访贝内特先生时，我问他是否担心这次合作可能会被认为是卖光了。 “我的梦想是让爵士乐走出去，这样它就不会被遗忘，”他回答道。对于已经经历过国际明星经历的贝内特先生来说，让数百万年轻听众接触摇摆乐和爵士乐更令人满意。他有宿怨要算。</p><p>贝内特先生出生于 1926 年，在大萧条时期在纽约皇后区阿斯托里亚社区长大，在家唱歌、画画。在他 10 岁时父亲去世后，他的大家庭鼓励他进行艺术创作。一位艺术老师建议他继续唱歌，以防万一。</p><p>第二次世界大战期间参军后，他的歌唱生涯于 20 世纪 40 年代末在纽约的俱乐部开始。回到纽约后，他自称乔·巴里 (Joe Bari)，经常光顾爵士音乐家的聚会场所。</p><p> 1949 年，珀尔·贝利 (Pearl Bailey) 邀请贝内特先生在格林威治村的一家俱乐部为她开场，并敦促鲍勃·霍普 (Bob Hope) 来见他。霍普带着贝内特先生上路，把他的姓氏从贝内代托缩短为贝内特。 1950 年，贝内特先生与哥伦比亚唱片公司签约。</p><p>在 20 世纪 50 年代，他录制了几张爵士乐风格的专辑，其中最著名的是与吉他手 Chuck Wayne 合作的“Cloud 7”，以及与钢琴家 Ralph Sharon 合作的“The Beat of My Heart”</p>和领先的爵士打击乐手。 1962年，贝内特先生的《我把我的心留在了旧金山》在告示牌专辑排行榜上攀升至第五位，主打歌成为他的标志性歌曲。接下来是贝内特先生更喜欢的两张专辑——《I Wanna Be around》（1963 年）和《电影歌曲专辑》（1966 年）。<p></p><p>但 1964 年披头士乐队的到来和新一代摇滚歌手兼词曲作者的出现让美国歌曲集变得陈旧。 1967 年，具有摇滚精神的克莱夫·戴维斯 (Clive Davis) 接手哥伦比亚之后，贝内特先生面临着录制当代流行音乐的压力。 “有些歌曲让我身体不适，”贝内特在自传中说道。</p><p> 1972 年，贝内特一怒之下离开了哥伦比亚，随后他为小唱片公司录制的专辑均未能进入排行榜。在此期间，贝内特先生录制了两张专辑，他告诉我这是他职业生涯中最好的专辑——与爵士钢琴家比尔·埃文斯的二重唱唱片。</p><p> 70 年代末，贝内特先生陷入了困境。他吸食可卡因，四处寻找工作，还两次离婚。到 1979 年，贝内特先生已濒临破产。他情绪崩溃，向儿子丹尼和戴寻求帮助。他们还清了他的债务并开始重建他的职业生涯。</p><p>随后他的许多专辑都在 Billboard 200 排行榜上名列前茅，其中《Duets II》和《Cheek to Cheek》名列第一。他还与 Phil Woods、Wynton Marsalis 和 Bill Charlap 等爵士艺术家合作录制了专辑。 2001 年，Bennett 先生与妻子 Susan 创立了</p>纽约皇后区的弗兰克辛纳屈艺术学院是一所学生通过试镜入学的高中。<p></p><p> 《Duets II》是一个转折点。其中包括与艾米·怀恩豪斯 (Amy Winehouse) 合作的充满情感的《身体与灵魂》，艾米·怀恩豪斯在录制该歌曲后不久就去世了。 Bennett先生和Lady Gaga（Lady Gaga也出现在这张专辑中）在Lady Gaga获释后就开始讨论一起录制一张歌曲集标准的专辑。</p><p> 2018 年，我在班尼特先生的艺术工作室接受《华尔街日报》采访时，我问他为什么个人如此痴迷爵士乐。 “这让我保持诚实，”他轻声说道。 “这是一件自发的事情。你必须凭直觉唱歌，并希望那一刻是正确的。年轻人喜欢它。他们只需要知道他们有选择。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。迈尔斯是《为什么爵士乐会发生》和《Anatomy of 55 More Songs》（格罗夫出版社）的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 18:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tony-bennetts-heart-was-in-jazz-4ee11d48</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tony-bennetts-heart-was-in-jazz-4ee11d48<category>艺术评论</category><category>奖项</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>托尼·贝内特</category><category>奖项</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The World Behind the World’ Review: What the Brain Scan Misses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>神经科学家的研究就好像思想和感觉的作用微乎其微。意识无法绘制其流动图。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11216831118178654471904590076432707316158"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821062?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Steven Siewert/悉尼先驱晨报/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11216831118178654471904590076432707316158"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">朱利安·巴吉尼</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日中午 12:02 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-behind-the-world-review-what-the-brain-scan-misses-6033e7ad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>想象一下，你可以将自己缩小到足以在大脑中旅行的程度。登上海马体或绕小脑航行无疑是一次很棒的体验，非常值得一游。但你在任何地方都无法体验有大脑的人在想什么、听什么或感觉什么。对你来说，有意识生命的嗡嗡作响的蜂巢只是细胞的集合。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/66a0226a-5841-4447-9fdf-b8e76f79cd70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>如此奇妙的旅程的局限性指向两种看似不可调和的看待我们自己的方式：作为生物物质和作为自我意识的心灵。这种对比几个世纪以来一直困扰着哲学家和科学家，有时会从客观与主观、外部与内部的角度来界定。神经科学家埃里克·霍尔（Erik Hoel）研究了人类自我感知的这两个领域，将它们称为外在观点和内在观点。在《世界背后的世界》一书中，他试图解释它们为何存在、我们如何尝试将它们纳入共识以及为什么我们可能永远不会完全成功。最重要的是，他试图反驳如今越来越频繁的论点，即神经元的放电（而不是思想和欲望）是人类行为的唯一真正原因。似乎这还不够，他试图用 200 多页的篇幅来保存我们也有自由意志的观点。他承认，他的项目“在范围上是不可能的”，但他仍然大胆地尝试一下。</p><p>霍尔先生首先挑战了这样一种观点，即内部和外部的双重视角是人类经验中长期不变的特征。相反，他认为内在的观点需要一段时间才能形成自己的观点。他说，自荷马时代以来，我们描述和表达内心世界的能力已经有了很大的发展。最早的骚动可以在古希腊作家身上看到，比如西蒙尼德斯，他开发了“记忆宫殿”的记忆方法，而欧里庇得斯则表达了他笔下人物的内心生活。霍尔先生说，这种观点在中世纪时期已经衰落，但在文艺复兴时期被塞万提斯等作家赋予了新的生命，并随着 18 世纪小说的兴起而得到进一步发展。</p><p>这个论点是推测性的，时间线太简洁了，但关键点是精心设计的：意识可能是人类的普遍性，但我们表达其品质并将其明确识别为独特视角的愿望和能力是人类变量，并不比我们科学地研究世界的能力更天生。事实上，霍尔先生说，科学的兴起也取决于我们学习一种观点——外在的观点。他以更快的速度简要介绍了这一发展过程。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>人类意识的挑战性科学、观察历史循环、奥尔曼兄弟的南方摇滚配方等等。</p></div></div><p>但随后，在这本书最有趣的一章中，霍尔先生改变了策略，认为神经科学的成就——外在自我审视的典型模式——远远低于炒作和头条新闻所暗示的。我们得到了如此多的承诺，仿佛对大脑细胞集合的仔细研究将为意识提供完整的解释。霍尔先生说，事实是，绘制大脑神经元活动图为我们提供的预测信息非常少。例如，你无法通过脑部扫描来可靠地判断某人是否患有抑郁症。大脑的可塑性太强，结构太不稳定，而且太复杂，扫描无法精确定位神经元水平上的作用以及任何特定的神经活动模式会产生什么影响。</p><p>但还有一个更深层次的问题。神经科学假设它可以纯粹通过采用外在的观点来进行。然而，正如我们假设的大脑周围的微型旅程所表明的那样，这种观点有严重的局限性——几乎从定义上来说，它排除了意识本身。神经科学家继续认为这种排除并不重要。霍尔先生写道，他们倾向于将意识视为“大脑的某种最小子系统，不拥有任何信息，几乎毫无用处。来自发动机的蒸汽。”霍尔先生认为，“我们作为一个有机体的生存”取决于意识及其准确跟踪现实的能力，或者用他的话说，取决于“始终真实且信息丰富的意识流”。他补充道，“除了意识之外”，大脑中没有任何东西是有意义的。</p><p>至此，霍尔先生巧妙地为另一场旋风之旅做好了准备，这一次调查了来自心理学和神经科学的意识理论。但这里的情况变得更加艰难。为了混合隐喻，读者面临着陡峭的学习曲线，即使在最好的情况下也很不稳定。霍尔先生开始使用逻辑真值表，就好像它们像条形图一样易于阅读，但这并没有帮助。</p><p>霍尔先生的主要研究方向是由神经科学家朱利奥·托诺尼 (Giulio Tononi) 开发的综合信息理论。粗略地说，它的中心论点是，物理系统整合信息的能力越强，它的意识就越强。这种整合（将不同信息元素组合在一起的能力）是通过标记为“phi”的单位来衡量的。该理论称，如果能够准确计算 phi，它就可以预测任何系统（人类、动物或机器）的意识水平。霍尔先生本人花了数年时间研究综合信息理论，但最终对此感到不满意。他认为，它可能描述了意识系统的某些关键特征，但它却无法解释意识本身。</p><p>霍尔先生得出了一个有些悲观的结论，即正如哥德尔表明数学或逻辑中没有任何形式系统可能是完整的一样，科学也许永远无法解释内在的观点。但读者并没有陷入这种低调。 《世界背后的世界》的最后几章捍卫了意识体验的作用。霍尔先生正在挑战那些坚持认为由于所有物理系统（我们也是其中之一）都无情地遵循因果规则，因此自由意志是一种幻觉的人。他的论点复杂而微妙，但本质上它等于一个简单的想法，即什么算作因果关系取决于规模。</p><p>例如，你无法通过分析大气中单个原子的运动来判断是否会下雨或刮飓风。你必须着眼于更大、更具包容性的尺度，即气压系统和云的形成。因为只有这个级别的事件才能解释和预测天气事件，所以我们正确地说它们是天气事件的原因。同样，单个神经元的放电模式并不能告诉你一个人将如何行动。但某人的想法和感受可能会这样做。霍尔先生说，这些心态被正确地称为行动原因：它们具有细胞所不具备的“能动性”。</p><p>霍尔先生似乎还没有承担足够的责任，他最后解决了自由意志这个棘手的问题。他的结论表明了这项任务的雄心：“拥有自由意志意味着成为在相关描述层面上因果出现的代理人，对他来说，最近的内部状态在因果上比遥远的过去状态更相关，并且在计算上是不可约的。”这是一个完全合理的建议，但它需要超过 13 页的篇幅才能清楚地表达其含义，更不用说为它建立一个案例了。</p><p> 《世界背后的世界》试图做得太多、太快，因此有时很难跟上，有时虽然有启发性，但并不真正有说服力。但它提供了一系列令人振奋的智力挑战，并且在其简洁的演示中，几乎看起来就像是一组至少六本你想读的其他书籍的戏弄散文预告片。霍尔先生还很年轻：他有时间和才华来写它们。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。巴吉尼是《重获自由：自由意志的可能性》一书的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 16:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-behind-the-world-review-what-the-brain-scan-misses-6033e7ad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-behind-the-world-review-what-the-brain-scan-misses-6033e7ad<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Fourth Turning Is Here’ and ‘End Times’ Review: Big Wheel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国历史的循环观是否预示着一场即将到来的政治危机——以及如何应对这场危机？ <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590095991034279562"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821120?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590095991034279562"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">多米尼克·格林</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 11:59 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fourth-turning-is-here-and-end-times-3439006b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>如果历史学家能够预测未来，他们的报酬就会更高。他们已经很难讲述过去了。历史不断被改写，因为不可能不从现在开始书写。预测是经济学家的事，但他们的学科令人失望的结果解释了为什么托马斯·卡莱尔称其为“令人沮丧的科学”。但那时，他是一位历史学家。</p><p>尼尔·豪（Neil Howe）和彼得·图尔钦（Peter Turchin）采用不同但具有启发性的方法来书写当前和不久的将来的预测性“大历史”。每个人都曾写过对未来进行过令人印象深刻的预测的书籍。两者都检测到我们经验的日常波动中的深层循环模式。两人都认为美国现在正陷入一场危机，其解决方案将在 2030 年代改变美国社会及其在世界上的地位。</p><p> 1997年，豪和威廉·施特劳斯出版了《第四次转折》，描述了英美历史上更新、稳定、衰落和危机的四代人循环。每一代“转变”大约需要20年，所以一个完整的周期大约需要80年。当前的周期始于 1946 年。豪和施特劳斯预测，其第四个转折点，即国内冲突的“危机”阶段，将在 2020 年左右达到高潮，然后在 2026 年左右通过经济重组成功解决。事实并非如此，但它足以表明历史周期理论的价值。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/6c46fec9-0736-4447-a333-fef0b333e840.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “旧的美利坚共和国正在崩溃，”豪先生在《第四次转折来了》中写道。豪先生的第四个转折，就像他的周期一样，包含子阶段。当前危机的“前兆”是 9/11 后的反恐战争。 “催化剂”是 2008 年的金融危机和随之而来的大衰退。第一次“重生”是2016年的选举，该选举将国家划分为“两个党派不可调和的阵营”。我们现在面临着“ekpyrosis”，这个术语源自斯多葛派哲学家的观点，即宇宙周期性地自我毁灭和重建。</p><p>正如建筑项目经常发生的那样，竣工时间被推迟。人们的寿命比之前的周期更长，因此 80 年的周期（豪先生称之为“saeculum”）可以延长至 92 年。这场危机的开始时间比预期要晚，结束时间也会更晚，“在 2030 年代中期的某个时候”。我们很快就会离开“破坏性阶段”，进入“建设性阶段”。这并不像听起来那样令人欢呼，因为建设性阶段也具有高度破坏性。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>人类意识的挑战性科学、观察历史循环、奥尔曼兄弟的南方摇滚配方等等。</p></div></div><p> “与外部侵略者进行全面斗争”和“内部政治革命或内战”的风险随着危机而达到顶峰。这些可能会导致国内彻底崩溃，就像过去一样（英国的玫瑰战争、美国内战）。或者，一个派系可以实现国内主导地位，并领导“一个统一的国家与外部敌人发生一场决定性的冲突”（伊丽莎白·英格兰对抗西班牙无敌舰队，罗斯福总统对抗轴心国）。第二次重生，“可能”通过选举，“可能”通过政党领导层的更迭，可以防止流血事件。但“无限期的僵局”将“打破历史格局”。</p><p>豪先生的理论以代际心理学和荣格原型为基础。艺术家一代的“敏感的年轻人”在第一次转折中成长，这是一个“加强机构的乐观时代”。在我们的社会中，这是杜鲁门、艾森豪威尔和肯尼迪总统以及沉默的一代（1925-42 年出生）的“美国高层”。第二次转折是一个“觉醒”，一个“精神剧变的激情时代”，先知一代的“挑衅的年轻十字军”用新的价值观挑战公民秩序。这就是始于 20 世纪 60 年代中期的意识革命，以婴儿潮一代（出生于 1943-60 年）为先知。</p><p>随着旧政权的衰弱和新价值观的扎根，第三次转折是个人主义、制度弱化和社会“瓦解”的时代。游牧一代（X 世代，生于 1961-81 年）是“异化的年轻人”，他们在文化战争和政治中心主义的崩溃中成长。第四次转折使他们成为应对危机的“务实的中年领导者”。他们为“英雄”一代和新的高度扫清了道路。最后的英雄是大兵一代（出生于 1901-24 年）；当前的英雄是千禧一代（1982-2005 年出生）。统治下一个美国的艺术家将是 Z 世代，或者豪先生所说的“家园者”。</p><p>豪预测婴儿潮一代的黄昏。 2029 年 4 月 13 日，以“埃及黑暗恶魔蛇”命名的大型小行星阿波菲斯将“距离地球非常危险，肉眼很容易就能看到”。倾向于“焦土政治”和“最后通牒和灾难的语言”的婴儿潮一代将拥抱“衰落和死亡的新道德”，并对眼前的一切征税。</p><p>作为“二战以来最尚武的老一辈”，他们会劝告年轻的美国人做出牺牲，但“他们要求的牺牲远远超过未来的回报”。年轻人会认为这是“无能，甚至是妄想”。只有X世代的游牧民族才能缓和“婴儿潮一代牧师战士”的求死热情，并阻止“一些正义的老水瓶座人”“把世界的灯熄灭”。</p><p>豪先生确定了这个过程及其情绪，但没有确定其原因或机制。 “英美”理想将会胜利，因为历史精神要求它。过去的英美危机“基本上得到了成功的解决”，因此美国人可能会期待一个“充满奇迹的世界”，他们的城市复兴，经济繁荣，出生率上升，美国引领“社会民主的全球生育主义改造”。但如果美国人不再认为自己属于“盎格鲁”社会呢？如果美国因大国冲突或“自我毁灭性内战”而“受到损害和削弱”，或者“其政治宪法急剧退化”怎么办？水晶球一片空白，前景严峻。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/0c7d2e59-bc45-4080-a017-23a0089318d2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>彼得·图尔钦 (Peter Turchin) 对理想主义、英美例外论或原型不太感兴趣。他在苏联长大，是一位受过训练的生物学家和一位数据处理专家。图尔钦先生在《末日：精英、反精英和政治瓦解之路》一书中提出了一种清晰而优雅的理论，该理论以自然法则和科学发现的方式跨越时间和地点而保持稳定。如果说豪先生的愿景充满了占星学的洛可可风格，那么图尔钦先生的愿景则具有社会科学的尖锐优雅。命运是数据流，而不是世代特征。他将其称为“cliodynamics”，以希腊历史缪斯克利奥（Clio）的名字命名。它可能发生在这里，因为它总是发生在任何地方。</p><p>对图尔钦来说，帝国和大国是“在一体化和瓦解阶段之间摆动的节拍器”。他只看到美国历史上政治两极分化的“两个大周期”。第一次是从 1830 年到 1930 年； 1920年左右的南北战争和劳工骚乱达到顶峰，1930年至1970年间贫富差距缩小的“大压缩”才得到解决。第二次两极分化始于1970年，贫富差距再次拉大，很快就会达到顶峰。贫富差距扩大是因为富有和人脉广泛的人为了自身利益而打开“财富泵”。社会学家称之为“寡头政治铁律”。这导致公众信任度下降、公共债务激增、实际工资价值下降以及对赞助的激烈竞争。</p><p>这种竞争武装了革命机制：“精英生产过剩”、“拥有高级学位的年轻毕业生生产过剩”。法国和俄国革命表明，“真正危险的革命者”是“失意的精英有志者”，尤其是律师。美国“越来越多的有资格的年轻人”“注定会成为受过教育的不稳定阶层”。他们“除了不稳定之外没有什么可失去的”，而且他们不会悄悄地“检查自己的特权”。想想#MeToo、“黑人的命也是命”、取消文化，以及社交媒体上对 JK 罗琳所谓的“变性恐惧症”进行的塞勒姆式的政治迫害。也许这就是莎士比亚写下“我们要做的第一件事，杀死所有律师”的原因。</p><p>图尔钦先生提出了一个三阶段的政治演变。在危机前，这个摇摇欲坠的国家面临着来自不同精英派系的多重挑战。在危机阶段，合法性的丧失会导致国家崩溃和精英内部争夺战利品的冲突。最终，“新的权力垄断”出现了。获胜者的重点是“获得对重建的政治、宗教和社会机构的常规接受”。我们“显然正处于从危机前到危机的过渡期”。</p><p>特朗普就任总统后，美国因“精英生产过剩和民众贫困”而处于“国家崩溃的边缘”。国家“面对众多反精英挑战者，从觉醒左派到新右派，努力维持对意识形态格局的控制”。他声称，当今美国的“结构状况”与其说是 20 世纪 70 年代的美国，不如说是“其他革命前的社会，例如 19 世纪末的俄罗斯”。正如俄罗斯革命者常说的，该怎么办？</p><p>十九世纪的英国通过移民、工业独创性以及最重要的将政治权力从地主士绅转移到“向上流动的商业精英”的制度改革，减轻了精英生产过剩和大规模贫困的压力。美国在进步时代“关闭了财富泵”，但在 20 世纪 70 年代却允许“自私精英”重新开启它。图尔钦警告说，解决这场危机需要“统治阶级具备一定的能力”。</p><p>未来总是不被书写的，但这并不意味着它不应该被书写。阅读先知书总是有好处的。豪先生的基于世代的计划可能看起来很奇怪，但回想起来，我们确实经常同意每一代人都有自己的性格。那么为什么不展望未来呢？ 《第四次转折来了》是宏大的历史和大胆的未来学，而且越贴近当下，就越显得合理。图尔钦先生既是一位过去主义者，也是一位未来主义者，他的理性方法让《末世》合理地确定了美国历史现在正在转向的一个枢纽。</p><p>这些书在方法和范围上如此不同，但却是相辅相成的。距离危机爆发还有大约十年的时间，所以有足够的时间阅读这两篇文章。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。格林是《期刊》撰稿人，也是皇家历史学会会员。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fourth-turning-is-here-and-end-times-3439006b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fourth-turning-is-here-and-end-times-3439006b<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>历史</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>历史</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Kings of Their Own Ocean’ Review: The Trouble With Tuna]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>海洋边界的建立是为了恢复蓝鳍金枪鱼的数量，将大西洋划分为截然不同的捕鱼区。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590087792939866272"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820744?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">地中海中，一群大西洋蓝鳍金枪鱼被渔网包围。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：anbusiello R/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590087792939866272"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">理查德·亚当斯·凯里</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 11:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kings-of-their-own-ocean-review-the-trouble-with-tuna-97c98c24"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>鱼儿在水的掩护下，想去哪儿就去哪儿。他们一直这样做，令渔民以及最近那些负责计算海中鱼类并仅授予可持续捕捞许可的官僚、科学家和数学家感到懊恼。</p><p>世界上几乎 90% 的海洋渔业已经被充分开发或过度捕捞，说起来容易做起来难。每种鱼类都是其高风险故事中的参与者，但一些最好的故事都发生在那些愿意花高价购买海鲜的人所珍视的鱼类身上：例如，鲟鱼，其乳白色的卵可能会变成鱼子酱;或者是蓝鳍金枪鱼，其浓密的红色腹肉是最令人向往的寿司中必不可少的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/5a32cc7c-2e39-4c66-a921-e34a898d84e8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>金枪鱼有 15 种，但在凯伦·平钦 (Karen Pinchin) 的《他们自己的海洋之王：金枪鱼、痴迷和我们海洋的未来》中，焦点完全集中在大西洋蓝鳍金枪鱼身上，它是一种快速的温血掠食者，是一种生理奇迹，已知长度可达近 13 英尺，重量可达 1,500 磅。平钦女士是一名加拿大记者，她的叙述围绕着一条特殊的蓝鳍金枪鱼，一条名叫阿米莉亚的雌性蓝鳍金枪鱼，以及 2004 年 9 月的一天在罗德岛海峡抓住她、标记她并释放她的痴迷包租船船长。</p><p>这个故事的第三个维度是由蓝鳍金枪鱼捕捞国家联盟于 1981 年在水中绘制的一条线。这条锯齿形拉链位于大西洋中部（以西经 45 度左右为中心），旨在遏制 20 世纪 70 年代以寿司为主导的对该物种的过度捕捞，反映出这样一种信念，即大西洋东部和西部的蓝鳍金枪鱼由两个独立的种群组成，因此可以单独管理。 “一夜之间，这条概念线改变了大西洋蓝鳍金枪鱼的渔业，”平钦女士写道。 “在大西洋的欧洲一侧，收成仍然是混战，对于历史上在这些水域捕捞的国家来说，可以捕获和杀死多少鱼没有配额。对于北美来说，对于包括美国和加拿大在内的国家（以及出于历史原因的日本）来说，除了那些据称是为了‘科学目的’而捕获的鱼之外，没有任何一条鱼是可以合法捕获的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The challenging science of human consciousness, watching history&#39;s cycles, the Allman Brothers&#39; Southern rock recipe and more.</p></div></div><p> Europeans stood by their higher numbers for bluefins in the sea, and Japanese buyers schooled to the Mediterranean. Meanwhile, Rhode Island boat captain Al Anderson—who since his youth had been tagging fish to feed his own curiosity, and in so doing forged contacts and alliances in the scientific community—continued helping his charter clients catch bluefins on a catch-tag-and-release basis.</p><p> Ms. Pinchin writes acutely about the codependence between fisheries science and politics. The two-stock theory, in fact, never held much water. As early as 1976, an Anderson-tagged bluefin had been recaptured in Europe&#39;s Bay of Biscay. But in 1981, the theory provided the North American delegation a means to claim control of at least half the Atlantic bluefin harvest, and so provide a lifeline for the species, “given,” writes Ms. Pinchin, “European countries&#39; refusal to reduce their catches.”</p><p> The author tries to have it both ways in exalting the 2018 death of Amelia—by gunshot, in a Portuguese set net—along with the return of her “twisted, weathered tag” to the National Marine Fisheries Service as the evidence-based death knell of what was always merely a policy construct. But it makes for good storytelling, as well as a point of entry into Ms. Pinchin&#39;s deft portraits of such as the revered, if irascible, Capt. Anderson and his wife, Daryl. The policy debates of recent decades are personified in the public wrangling between the prominent ecologist Carl Safina, who argues for the most stringent protections for bluefins, and the scientist Molly Lutcavage, who scrabbles for grants, argues for less in the way of politics and more by way of hard science in bluefin policy, and who herself—in 2007—captured and tagged the peripatetic Amelia off Cape Cod.</p><p> There are other rich characters here as well, and fascinating excursions into the cul-de-sacs of this world, such as the annual bluefin sportfishing tournament that drew international anglers, celebrities and millions of dollars in today&#39;s money to two little towns in Nova Scotia—until the tuna disappeared in the 1970s. That was when a fish previously considered only marginally edible suddenly became a lucrative delicacy, and Ms. Pinchin deliciously describes the Rev. Sun Myung Moon&#39;s strenuous efforts to build a vertically integrated operation—boats, processors, distributors—that would corner the world&#39;s bluefin market for his Unification Church and make its founder, as Moon described himself then, “King of the Ocean.”</p><p> Some material feels like padding—do we need the speeches made at Capt. Anderson&#39;s induction into a game-fishing hall of fame?—while it seems an omission that a story as free-range as Amelia herself should not take stock of the growing bluefin farming industry, where some 15 pounds of mackerel and herring are required as feed to produce each pound of bluefin belly meat. Such hollowing out of the ocean&#39;s food chain portends to have something to do, I think, with “the future of our seas.”</p><p> In her final chapter, Ms. Pinchin ties her wide-angle, free-wheeling story together by recalling what she terms “butterfly-wing events”: small moments in the lives of her characters, little tricks of circumstance, that have played to momentous effect on the Atlantic bluefin and the hardscrabble fishing communities that have donned the “golden handcuffs” that come with temporary infusions of foreign cash. In the Portuguese villages near where Amelia was taken for sushi, this has meant criminal networks, cross-border smuggling and depleted waters.</p><p> Those butterfly-beats powerfully encapsulate the intimate interdependence of predator and prey, especially when human predators flatten a wild prey animal into an economic commodity and allow short-term self-interest—well, greed—to push predation past that invisible threshold between sustainability and a spiral to extinction. “Diving into the history of bluefin and the human communities that have lived alongside the species for millennia,” Ms. Pinchin writes, “I glimpsed a vision of a reciprocal future, one in which human passions could dovetail with our long-term survival on this planet—a quest that must include the right of wildlife to thrive alongside us.”</p><p> To that end, the author argues, we all need some version of that 45-degree line. Certainly we do, simply because we keep proving that we are—like Lucifer in the Rolling Stones&#39; “Sympathy for the Devil”—“in need of some restraint.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Carey&#39;s books include “Against the Tide: The Fate of the New England Fisherman” and “The Philosopher Fish: Sturgeon, Caviar, and the Geography of Desire.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kings-of-their-own-ocean-review-the-trouble-with-tuna-97c98c24</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kings-of-their-own-ocean-review-the-trouble-with-tuna-97c98c24<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>natural environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Sergey Brin Is Back in the Trenches at Google]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>联合创始人正在与科技巨头总部的人工智能研究人员一起工作，协助建立强大的 Gemini 系统<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="577" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821144?width=860&amp;height=577" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林长期以来对人工智能技术很感兴趣，他定期与参与人工智能研究的谷歌员工会面。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JUNG YEON-JE/​​法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈尔斯·克鲁帕</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 10:10（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林重返工作岗位。</p><p>近几个月来，这位亿万富翁每周都会访问这家科技巨头位于加州山景城的办公室，通常每周三到四天，与研究人员一起努力开发该公司的下一个大型人工智能系统。</p><p>知情人士称，布林去年年底参加了谷歌办公室有关人工智能的会议，但他参与的频率和强度有所增加。他的新立场与他在 2019 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sundar-pichai-to-replace-larry-page-as-ceo-of-alphabet-11575409229?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞去</a>母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabet</a>高管职务后采取的相对不干涉的态度发生了显着变化。</p><p>他与一组研究人员密切合作，构建了谷歌期待已久的人工智能模型 Gemini。他们讨论了诸如“损失曲线”之类的技术问题，这是一种衡量人工智能程序随时间推移表现的方法，布林还每周与谷歌员工就新的人工智能研究进行讨论。知情人士称，他还干预人事事务，例如聘用受欢迎的研究人员。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，布林在谷歌的影响力增加反映了人工智能的关键时刻以及他对这项技术的长期兴趣。谷歌是该技术的先驱，但在将其转化为新产品方面比竞争对手慢。</p><p>随着 Meta Platforms 等公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-and-microsoft-team-up-to-distribute-new-ai-software-for-commercial-use-c4f7b634?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近推出的新产品</a>，人工智能研究领域的竞争正在加剧。谷歌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-tries-to-catch-up-to-rivals-like-openai-as-they-release-viral-apps-11674828418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了产品开发速度，</a>以应对去年发布的 ChatGPT，这是一款由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>支持的研究公司 OpenAI 开发的人工智能聊天机器人，可以流畅地响应一系列书面查询。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820793?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌创始人谢尔盖·布林和拉里·佩奇从斯坦福大学博士生起就一直在一起工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·内格尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Gemini 是 Google 尝试构建的<a href="https://blog.google/technology/ai/google-palm-2-ai-large-language-model/" target="_blank" class="icon none">通用人工智能</a>程序，可以与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/openai-rolls-out-updated-version-of-viral-chatbot-chatgpt-f03fea27?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenAI 的 GPT-4 模型</a>相媲美，该模型为 ChatGPT 的付费版本提供支持。据知情人士透露，负责该项目的谷歌高管德米斯·哈萨比斯 (Demis Hassabis) 在最近的一次全公司会议上告诉员工，该项目将于今年晚些时候推出。</p><p> 49 岁的布林于 1998 年与拉里·佩奇 (Larry Page) 一起创立了谷歌，他们在斯坦福大学攻读博士时共同进行了网络搜索研究。</p><p>虽然布林近年来偶尔出现在谷歌总部，但他的注意力主要集中在飞艇和新形式的灾难援助等外部利益上，以及捐赠部分巨额财富的努力。根据 S&amp;P Capital IQ 的数据，他是 Alphabet 的第二大个人股东，仅次于 Page，所持股份价值接近 900 亿美元。</p><p>自从谷歌在 5 月份的年度开发者大会上宣布一系列人工智能产品以来，Alphabet 的股价已经上涨了 10% 以上，其中包括新版本的核心搜索引擎，该引擎提供了冗长的摘要并邀请后续问题。这一涨幅与竞争对手微软的股价和更广泛的纳斯达克综合指数大致一致。</p><p>知情人士称，布林大部分时间都在新建的查尔斯顿东大楼里与山景城的人工智能研究人员坐在一起，该大楼距离谷歌公司园区原来的中心仅几步之遥。谷歌和 Alphabet 的首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊 (Sundar Pichai) 也在大楼内设有办公室。</p><p>四年前，当创始人辞去日常职务并将皮查伊提拔为 Alphabet 首席执行官时，他们表示将定期与他交谈并提供“建议和爱，但不会每天唠叨”。他们仍然控制着 Alphabet 的多数投票权，并与皮查伊一起担任执行董事会委员会成员。</p><p>据一位了解皮查伊想法的人士透露，皮查伊对布林的参与感到兴奋，并鼓励他做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="475" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820792?width=700&amp;height=475" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2012 年，谢尔盖·布林 (Sergey Brin) 与一辆自动驾驶汽车在谷歌山景城总部。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>谷歌在人工智能领域处于领先地位，于 2011 年成立了一个名为 Brain 的研究部门，研究如何使用称为深度学习的计算技术来构建广泛有用的人工智能程序。</p><p> Pichai 今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabets-google-combines-ai-research-units-brain-and-deepmind-620f4f7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将 Brain 团队与 DeepMind 合并</a>，DeepMind 是一家人工智能研究公司，此前在 Alphabet 旗下独立运营。这次改组将 DeepMind 联合创始人哈萨比斯提升为合并后的 Google DeepMind 集团的首席执行官。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，一些研究人员接受了布林的参与，认为这是对他们工作的认可，也是人工智能团队在过渡时期的有益干预。哈萨比斯和许多 Google DeepMind 高管在伦敦工作，使该办公室成为新设置中事实上的权力中心。</p><p>自 11 月份 ChatGPT 发布以来，布林的参与度不断增加。据《纽约时报》早些时候报道的知情人士透露，谷歌的联合创始人参加了会议，审查谷歌正在为 5 月份的开发者大会准备的人工智能产品。</p><p>此后，布林一直在谷歌总部保持着强大的影响力，经常出席研究聚会和公司庆祝活动。谷歌表示，除了联合创始人和董事会成员之外，布林在公司没有正式的新角色。布林的发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><p>佩奇在管理谷歌期间有时是一个隐居的人物，而布林却培养了一个更平易近人的形象，穿着溜冰鞋穿越总部，在公司的各个项目之间穿梭。</p><p>据与布林有过互动的人士透露，自从去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-in-talks-to-invest-200-million-into-ai-startup-11666381180?&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能热潮</a>以来，布林就参加了该公司的发布会，该公司推广了图像生成程序 Stable Diffusion，并且偶尔也会参加在加利福尼亚州希尔斯伯勒一座价值 6800 万美元的豪宅（即 AGI House）举行的活动。 AGI 代表通用人工智能，即计算机程序有一天可以与人类推理相匹配。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820384?width=700&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年早些时候，谷歌首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊、谢尔盖·布林、卢森堡首相泽维尔·贝特尔和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢森堡国务部</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年3月，在<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/xavier-bettel_thanks-to-sundar-pichai-and-kent-walker-activity-7041634974231351296-hDnQ/" target="_blank" class="icon none">卢森堡首相访问期间，布林被拍到与皮查伊和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克在谷歌总部合影</a>，布林身着灰色运动裤和黑色长袖衬衫。其他与会者都穿着西装。</p><p>布林与 Gemini 的合作是谷歌长期努力构建人工智能系统的又一成果，这些系统可以展现出类人的能力，并更无缝地满足该公司数十亿用户的需求。</p><p>布林在 2017 年 <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ffvu6Mr1SVc&amp;t=92s" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界经济论坛上接受采访</a>时表示，起初，布林忽视了 Brain 团队的工作，并对他们能否破解人工智能表示怀疑，尽管该团队始于他领导的 Google X 部门。</p><p> “说实话，我根本没有注意它，”布林说。他说，几年后，Brain 的研究被用于谷歌许多最大的产品，颠覆了他之前的假设。</p><p>布林在一定程度上关注了人事问题，随着人工智能研究人员的人才争夺战加剧，这对谷歌和其他大型科技公司来说是一个困难的领域。 2017 年，谷歌发表了一篇具有里程碑意义的论文，该论文被认为引发了最新一波人工智能发展浪潮，该论文的多位作者已离开该公司，为竞争对手的初创公司筹集数亿美元资金。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>谢尔盖·布林会让谷歌在人工智能领域更具竞争力吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现任和前任员工表示，尽管布林是世界上最受尊敬的计算机科学家之一，但他需要赶上人工智能的最新发展，并且没有为编码项目做出重大贡献。</p><p>布林在 2018 年发布的上一封股东信中宣传了人工智能的可能性，他写道，“计算解决重要问题的力量和潜力从未如此强大。”</p><p> “人工智能的新春天是我一生中计算领域最重大的发展，”他写道。</p><p>写信给 Miles Kruppa ( <a href="mailto:miles.kruppa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">miles.kruppa@wsj.com)</a>和 Deepa Seetharaman ( <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e<author><![CDATA[Miles KruppaDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母</category><category>谷歌</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>谢尔盖·布林</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Rise and Fall of the Chief Diversity Officer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Diversity executives hit the exits as company priorities shift; &#39;everything is a battle&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820139?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> From left: Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive; Dani Monroe, former CDO for Mass General Brigham; and Miriam Warren, CDO for Yelp.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo Illustration: Melinda Starbird, Cheryl Richard, Yelp </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/te-ping-chen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Te-Ping Chen</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lauren Weber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Two years ago chief diversity officers were some of the hottest hires into executive ranks. Now, they increasingly feel left out in the cold.</p><p> Companies including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="">Netflix</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="company-name">Disney</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="company-name">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> have recently said that high-profile diversity, equity and inclusion executives will be leaving their jobs. Thousands of diversity-focused workers have been laid off since last year, and some companies are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">scaling back</a> racial justice commitments.</p><p> Diversity, equity and inclusion—or DEI—jobs were put in the crosshairs after many companies started re-examining their executive ranks during the tech sector&#39;s shake out last fall. Some chief diversity officers say their work is facing additional scrutiny since the Supreme Court <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">struck down affirmative action</a> in college admissions and companies brace for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-attorneys-general-warn-top-u-s-businesses-over-discrimination-1eb78d29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">potential legal challenges</a> . DEI work has also become a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantiss-education-policies-leave-florida-teachers-feeling-unsure-3a81a236?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">political target</a> .</p><p> “There&#39;s a combination of grief, being very tired, and being, in some cases, overwhelmed,” says Miriam Warren, chief diversity officer for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELP" class="">Yelp</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> of the challenges facing executives in the field.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In interviews, current and former chief diversity officers said company executives at times didn&#39;t want to change hiring or promotion processes, despite initially telling CDOs they were hired to improve the talent pipeline. The quick about-face shows company enthusiasm for diversity initiatives hasn&#39;t always proved durable, leaving some diversity officers now questioning their career path.</p><p> In the wake of George Floyd&#39;s murder in police custody in May 2020, companies scrambled to hire chief diversity officers, changing the face of the C-suite. In 2018, less than half the companies in the S&amp;P 500 employed someone in the role, and by 2022 three out four companies had created a position, according to a study from Russell Reynolds, an executive search firm.</p><p> Once mostly tasked with HR matters, today&#39;s diversity leaders are expected to weigh in on new product development, marketing efforts and current events that have an impact on how workers and consumers are feeling. Warren and other CDOs said the expanded remit is playing out in a politically divided environment where corporate diversity efforts are the subject of frequent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-new-cause-dodging-the-culture-wars-73e52cf3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">social-media firestorms</a> .</p><h3> Falling demand</h3><p> New analysis from employment data provider Live Data Technologies shows that chief diversity officers have been more vulnerable to layoffs than their human resources counterparts, experiencing 40% higher turnover. Their job searches are also taking longer.</p><p> “I got to 300 applications and then I stopped tracking,” says Stephanie Lubin, who was laid off from her role as diversity head at Drizly, an online alcohol marketplace, in May following the company&#39;s acquisition by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p> In one case, Lubin says she went through 16 rounds of interviews for a role she didn&#39;t get, and says she is now planning to pivot out of DEI work.<p></p><p> The number of CDO searches is down 75% in the past year, says Jason Hanold, chief executive of Hanold Associates Executive Search, which works with Fortune 100 companies to recruit HR and DEI executives, among other roles. Demand is the lowest he has seen in his 30 years of recruiting.</p><p> At the same time, he says, more executives are feeling skittish about taking on diversity roles.</p><p> “They&#39;re telling us, the only way I want to go into another role with DEI is if it includes something else,” he says of the requests for broader titles that offer more responsibilities and resources. He estimates that 60% of diversity roles he is currently filling combine the title with another position, such as chief human resources officer, up from about 10% five years ago.</p><p> During the pandemic, some companies moved people into diversity leadership if they were an ethnic minority, says</p> Dani Monroe, even when they weren&#39;t qualified. Monroe served as CDO for Mass General Brigham, a Boston-based hospital system and one of the largest employers in the state, until 2021 and convenes a yearly gathering of more than 100 CDOs.<p></p><p> “These were knee-jerk reactions,” she says of the hurried CDO hires, adding that some of those elevations didn&#39;t create much impact, leaving both sides feeling disillusioned.</p><h3> On-the-job obstruction</h3><p> American workers are split on the importance of a diverse workforce, <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2023/05/17/diversity-equity-and-inclusion-in-the-workplace/" target="_blank" class="icon none">surveys find</a> .</p><p> Diversity chiefs also encounter obstruction from top executives, says Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive who has worked at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/T" class="">AT&amp;T</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">Starbucks</a> and OfferUp, an online marketplace. Leaders sometimes associate diversity efforts with mandates, such as the equal-employment rules that apply to federal contractors. Those requirements for compliance can create executive resistance that bleeds over into other cultural or policy shifts, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">adding Juneteenth</a> as a company holiday, she says.<p></p><p> “Even if you report to the CEO, it&#39;s still a battle and it&#39;s a smaller budget,” says Starbird, who was laid off from OfferUp in November during a broader restructuring.</p><p> Many diversity executives feel a lack of buy-in from their colleagues. In <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://world50.com/impact?utm_source=wsj&amp;utm_medium=pr&amp;utm_campaign=2023idreport__;!!F0Stn7g!EGLdSj-lMiFGnMwE-GKlWcgVj1tXMu0_-ZbTIyBUUYuQV0JylSZhtrfPiJ-A4c5JWSBx3Po2kxjQHsQPCw$" target="_blank" class="icon none">a survey</a> of 138 diversity executives conducted this spring by World 50 Group, a networking organization for corporate leaders, 82% said they had sufficient influence to do their job, down 6 percentage points from 2022. Asked if they felt supported by middle managers, 41% said yes, an 8-percentage-point drop.</p><p> Since the Supreme Court overturned affirmative action in June, companies are anticipating spillover legal action could have an impact on them. Those that are still hiring CDOs want people who can help the board navigate the political and legal landscape of diversity work and figure out how to take defensive moves to shield them from litigation, says Tina Shah Paikeday, global leader of Russell Reynolds&#39;s diversity, equity and inclusion practice.</p><p> “They recognize it would be smart to get ahead of that.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820155?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, says efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nielsen</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> People are more resistant to company-backed efforts to advance diversity when they are worried about their own jobs, whether because of impending layoffs or disruptions from AI, says David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, the media-ratings company.</p><p> Kenny was both CEO and CDO for a time, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-executive-or-diversity-chief-nielsens-ceo-is-both-11608908446?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking on</a> the diversity role to emphasize how important it was to the future of the business. Even as CEO, it could be a tough sell. Efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p> “A lot of it is, &#39;I&#39;m losing my slice of the pie,&#39; ” he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/9d40dc7b-c819-4785-ab9c-4c1e1272d3a7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Te-Ping Chen at <a href="mailto:Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bef2e1de-18c2-41e5-86fb-8b21bfe3c1c7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f<author><![CDATA[Te-Ping ChenLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>Human Resources Consulting</category><category> Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category> Accounting/Consulting</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Business Consultancy</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Diversity</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Netflix</category><category> NFLX</category><category> Walt Disney</category><category> DIS</category><category> AT&amp;T</category><category> T</category><category> Warner Bros. Discovery Inc. Series A</category><category> WBD</category><category> Warner Bros. Discovery</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace diversity</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>human resources consulting</category><category> broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category> accounting</category><category> consulting</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>business consultancy</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[America’s Rise as Energy Export Powerhouse Hinges on One Town]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Pipelines to Corpus Christi, Texas, are near capacity as US oil production approaches records <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821191/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="About 2 million barrels of daily crude exports passed through Corpus Christi, Texas, in the first half of 2023, in addition to refined fuels." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> About 2 million barrels of daily crude exports passed through Corpus Christi, Texas, in the first half of 2023, in addition to refined fuels. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071302"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071302"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-uberti" itemprop="url" rel="author">David Uberti</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-morenne" itemprop="url" rel="author">Benoît Morenne</a></span> | Photographs by Verónica G. Cárdenas for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-rise-as-an-energy-export-powerhouse-hinges-on-one-town-831518c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The US has transformed global markets by boosting crude-oil exports more than 30-fold over the past decade. Much of the boom hinges on Corpus Christi Bay.</p><p> In the first four months of 2023, about half of the country&#39;s 4.1 million barrels of daily shipments abroad was loaded onto skyscraper-size tankers from this stretch of Texas coastline, destined to become fuel for overseas travelers or factories. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821234?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> That <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-oil-boom-blunts-opecs-pricing-power-472567f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">gusher of supply</a> has helped blunt the increase in prices from recent production cuts by Saudi Arabia and Russia. In Europe, oil and natural gas shipped from the Gulf Coast <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-regains-its-energy-clout-as-ukraine-war-enters-second-year-2b910ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have backstopped the continent</a> as it weaned itself off Russian energy after the outbreak of the war on Ukraine.</p><p> Corpus Christi has become the dominant US hub, siphoning crude from elsewhere thanks to unique terminals that make it cheaper than competitors. Now, ballooning trade from the port has put the US on pace to pump out record oil exports this year, according to federal record-keepers.</p><p> But with pipelines nearing capacity and US output set to reach new heights, competition is heating up among companies and investors over how to connect the American oil patch to a fuel-hungry world.</p><p> “The market is totally focused on taking shale production from the US into international markets,” said Rusty Braziel, chief executive of consulting firm RBN Energy.</p><p> Corpus Christi is the closest deep-draft port to the Permian Basin in West Texas and New Mexico, America&#39;s hottest oil field. Crude extracted from shale rock there, prized by overseas refineries for its light, sweet quality, trades at a premium to many other grades. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a3d36427-a351-47de-864b-cce33645a7a6.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> That oil was confined stateside as the shale boom unleashed unprecedented US production growth. But after Washington nixed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/congressional-leaders-agree-to-lift-40-year-ban-on-oil-exports-1450242995?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">decades-old export restrictions</a> in 2015, companies scrambled to build out pipelines to Corpus Christi, a South Texas city of about 320,000.</p><p> Various companies have since constructed storage tanks in Corpus Christi to hold tens of millions more barrels of oil near the water. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LNG" class="company-name">Cheniere Energy</a></p> is expanding a plant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-fracked-gas-ukraine-invasion-europe-import-9e5cc725?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">that can liquefy natural gas</a> for export. Since 2020, dredgers have been at work deepening the port&#39;s ship channel and inner harbor to 54 feet from 47 feet currently, a more than $680 million operation that will allow many tankers to fill up close to capacity.<p></p><p> “You can&#39;t just build those facilities overnight,” said Kent Britton, the Port of Corpus Christi&#39;s interim chief executive. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821161?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Ensuing growth in crude shipments has outpaced other launch points in Texas and Louisiana largely because of the economics of shipping. Exporters that operate from Houston-Galveston and the main Port of Corpus Christi funnel shipments to smaller classes of tankers, which either carry cargoes abroad or ferry them to 1,100-foot supertankers anchored offshore in a dayslong process.</p><p> But across Corpus Christi Bay, in the small town of Ingleside, Texas, oil terminals at a former Naval base are big enough that those massive ships can fill up about half of their 2 million barrels of capacity from shore.</p><p> “You can pretty much load your million barrels in 24 hours,” said Lois Zabrocky, chief executive of</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/INSW" class="">International Seaways</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which operates 13 so-called very large crude carriers.<p></p><p> Five tugboats then guide half-full VLCCs several miles out to sea, where smaller tankers top them off for delivery to refineries in Europe, Asia or elsewhere. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821156?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> That streamlined loading process can pare the price of shipments compared with elsewhere on the Gulf Coast. Analysts said such differences became particularly crucial last year after Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine whipsawed energy markets and sent shipping costs skyrocketing.</p><p> Calgary, Alberta-based <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CA/XTSE/GEI" class="company-name">Gibson Energy</a> bought one of the Ingleside terminals in June for $1.1 billion, an investment that Chief Executive</p> Steven Spaulding said will pay off regardless of whether Permian production growth continues. His rationale: Ingleside&#39;s efficiency will entice traders, even if it means drawing oil away from across Corpus Christi Bay.<p></p><p> “It doesn&#39;t matter to our terminal,” Spaulding said.</p><p> Pipelines from the Permian to Corpus Christi are running at about 90% capacity, according to East Daley Analytics, a level at which traders might begin sending more crude toward Houston for refining or shipment abroad.</p><p> The midstream energy company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ENB" class="company-name">Enbridge</a> has responded by announcing an expansion of its pipeline to Corpus Christi by 200,000 barrels a day. Other companies have proposed environmentally contentious plans for multibillion-dollar deepwater terminals that would allow VLCCs to load up fully in the Gulf of Mexico. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821198?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A liquid terminal in Ingleside, Texas, a port with capacity to accommodate supertankers.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For all their customers&#39; focus on oil-and-gas exports, Corpus officials are preparing for a future when the US exports nonfossil-fuel commodities such as hydrogen and ammonia. The port authority applied to receive some of the $8 billion that Washington pledged in its 2021 infrastructure package to develop regional hubs aimed at accelerating the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/big-name-investors-pour-billions-into-clean-hydrogen-projects-11657792800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">use of hydrogen for energy</a> .</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What are the implications of Texas&#39; growing prominence in the global energy trade?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Enbridge has said it would partner with the Norwegian fertilizer company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YARIY" class="company-name">Yara International</a> to develop a plant to produce up to 1.4 million tons of ammonia a year at its Ingleside terminal. The companies plan to capture <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carbon-capture-projects-are-taking-off-heres-how-they-stash-the-greenhouse-gas-11666928082?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">carbon dioxide</a> produced during the process and store it underground—activity that could qualify for credits under President Biden&#39;s climate law.</p><p> Corpus Christi “is hopefully the gift that&#39;s going to keep on giving,” said Phil Anderson, senior vice president, business development, at Enbridge.</p><p> Write to David Uberti at <a href="mailto:david.uberti@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.uberti@wsj.com</a> and Benoît Morenne at <a href="mailto:benoit.morenne@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.morenne@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-rise-as-an-energy-export-powerhouse-hinges-on-one-town-831518c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-rise-as-an-energy-export-powerhouse-hinges-on-one-town-831518c<author><![CDATA[David UbertiBenoît Morenne]]></author><category> wsjfinance-markets</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>活力</category><category>Oil and Gas Upstream Operations</category><category> Oil extraction</category><category> Oil and Natural Gas Exploration</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>活力</category><category>oil and gas upstream operations</category><category> oil extraction</category><category> oil and natural gas exploration</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Where Is Kamala Harris?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Slow start to Biden 2024 campaigning comes as vice president contends with low approval ratings <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071890"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821223?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Vice President Kamala Harris gave a speech on abortion rights in Charlotte, NC, last month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Erik S. Lesser/PRESS POOL </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071890"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/catherine-lucey" itemprop="url" rel="author">Catherine Lucey</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 5:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Vice President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kamala-harris">Kamala Harris</a> planned <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kamala-harris-prepares-to-hit-the-road-for-biden-despite-cracks-in-her-support-45a4015d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to campaign extensively</a> for President Biden&#39;s re-election, but her early schedule suggests otherwise.</p><p> In the 10 weeks following Biden&#39;s campaign launch, the vice president has traveled to nine states—three of them considered battlegrounds in the 2024 election—and appeared at seven fundraisers, according to her calendar.</p><p> Biden&#39;s campaign said that Harris&#39;s early pace of campaigning was similar to Biden&#39;s in 2011 when he was vice president. President Biden has crisscrossed the country for a roughly similar number of campaign events during that time. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6D4E88DA-6C2C-4F8E-903E-A5D7F614F8C1&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwhere-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> WSJ&#39;s Ken Thomas breaks down how the political landscape has changed since 2020 and what challenges President Biden will face in 2024. Photo illustration: Ryan Trefes<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“While history has shown it is incredibly early for an incumbent ticket to campaign, already Vice President Harris is doing the important work of meeting and engaging with voters nationwide,” said campaign spokesman Kevin Munoz.<br><br> The campaign points out that she has visited Arizona this month and that her schedule is growing. On Friday, she plans to travel to Florida.</p><p> Some campaign donors expressed reservations about her abilities and said she didn&#39;t have the same appeal as Biden, with one fundraiser describing her as a “tough sell.”</p><p> “Speaking solely for myself, I don&#39;t think I would ever be able to have a very successful fundraiser with her as the headliner,” said Democratic donor and trial lawyer John Morgan. “First of all, for many people, Democrats included, she&#39;s polarizing.”</p><p> Republicans have sought to highlight the vice president&#39;s vulnerabilities. On Twitter, the Republican National Committee has pointed to flubs in speeches. Former South Carolina Gov. Nikki Haley, currently polling in the single digits in her bid for the 2024 GOP presidential nomination, has argued that voting for Biden is actually voting for Harris.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How do you think Kamala Harris can best contribute to President Biden&#39;s re-election campaign?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “We are running against Kamala Harris. Make no bones about it,” she said during a recent Fox News interview.</p><p> Many Democrats dismiss such attacks as unfair on the first Black woman to serve as vice president, noting that she is an effective messenger on core Democratic issues such as abortion and a popular figure among women, Black voters and young people. That was reflected in her schedule, which included speeches on abortion and gun violence.</p><p> “There&#39;s nobody in this administration who&#39;s more compelling and authentic but also persuasive on abortion than the vice president,” said Mini Timmaraju, president of Naral Pro-Choice America. “We&#39;re pleased with her presence. I fully expect to see a lot more.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821651?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Other Democrats would like to see her favorability ratings rise among voters so she is a more effective surrogate for the president, whose own poll numbers have been steady but low. They say that could be important as the campaign heats up: At 80 years old, Biden could face limitations in the amount of campaigning he can do. Harris is 58 years old.</p><p> Harris has an approval rating of around 40%, according to the FiveThirtyEight average of national polls, a similar rating to Biden&#39;s.</p><p> During the campaign&#39;s first 10 weeks, there were 30 days in which there were no public events on the vice president&#39;s schedule, many of those weekend days. The vice president&#39;s office said that there were activities not reflected on her schedule on some of those days, largely private meetings or press interviews.</p><p> Christine Sinicki, who chairs the Democratic Party of Milwaukee County, which includes the city of Milwaukee, said she wasn&#39;t worried that Harris hadn&#39;t traveled to Wisconsin yet. But she noted that Biden narrowly won the state in 2020. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821220?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Vice President Kamala Harris participating in a Martin Luther King Jr. Day service project in Washington, DC, in January.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Leigh Vogel/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We need to make sure we are doing everything we can to get those votes out,” she said, adding that Harris is popular there, particularly with women, including those among minorities. “We need to see the vice president here. Especially in places like Milwaukee.”</p><p> North Carolina Democratic Gov. Roy Cooper, who hosted Harris for a speech on abortion in June, said Harris had been to the state seven times since Biden was elected. “We&#39;re glad for every visit. And I think she&#39;s helping to make a real difference showing North Carolinians how the Biden-Harris administration is working for them,” he said.</p><p> The political-action committee Emily&#39;s List has begun airing a TV ad aimed at boosting Harris. The ad, also funded by the pro-Biden super PAC Future Forward, features Harris speaking about Republican efforts to restrict abortion access.</p><p> Democratic strategist Mary Anne Marsh said such efforts will be crucial for Harris. “They need to raise her favorability ratings so she&#39;s more effective as this goes on,” she said.</p><p> Some donors are expressing enthusiasm for Harris. Charles Myers, who hosted an event headlined by Harris in New York recently, told the room, “I will be very proud to be the first one to sign up for Harris for President 2028.”</p><p> So far, it appears that Harris&#39;s campaign efforts are suffering from some of the same trouble other vice presidents have faced in the job: making clear what it is, exactly, that they do.</p><p> The No. 2 doesn&#39;t set the White House agenda and can&#39;t publicly get ahead of Biden on policy or be seen as outshining him, Harris allies said. The same could be said for the campaign trail.</p><p> “The lesson you learn when you&#39;re in the office of the vice president is it is very difficult to win a battle about what she is doing,” said Matt Bennett, a former aide to Vice President Al Gore and co-founder of Third Way, a centrist think tank.</p><p> Write to Catherine Lucey at <a href="mailto:catherine.lucey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">catherine.lucey@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-kamala-harris-3ba86408<author><![CDATA[Catherine Lucey]]></author><category> Abortion</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Medical Treatments/Procedures</category><category>选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>卡玛拉·哈里斯</category><category>abortion</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>medical treatments</category><category> procedures</category><category>选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Jackie O.’s Collection of Homes Was as Iconic as It Gets]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A massive East Hampton estate. A sprawling New York City apartment. The properties where she lived before and after becoming first lady are some of the most coveted real estate in America <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818403/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, pictured in 1960, lived in an iconic collection of luxury homes." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, pictured in 1960, lived in an iconic collection of luxury homes. The Estate of Jacques Lowe/Getty Images <span>The Estate of Jacques Lowe/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055379"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055379"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eb-solomont" itemprop="url" rel="author">EB Solomont</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 21, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-o-s-collection-of-homes-was-as-iconic-as-it-gets-2500daf4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> When Eaddo and Peter D. Kiernan III first laid eyes on Hammersmith Farm in Newport, RI, in the 1990s, they loved it immediately.</p><p> Immortalized as the site of the 1953 wedding reception of Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy and John F. Kennedy, and later dubbed President Kennedy&#39;s summer White House, the circa-1880s estate overlooking Narragansett Bay hadn&#39;t been lived in for decades. But Kiernan, a self-described patriot who said he knew the late John F. Kennedy Jr. , realized instantly it would be the perfect summer home for his own sprawling Irish Catholic family.</p><p> The Kiernans purchased Hammersmith Farm for just over $8 million in 1999, and then spent more than 10 years restoring it, drawing on old sketches, photographs and stories shared by Jackie&#39;s stepbrother, Hugh D. “Yusha” Auchincloss III, whose family built the estate about a century before. “We would literally say, &#39;Tell us everything you can remember,&#39; ” said Kiernan, a former Goldman Sachs banker. When Auchincloss saw the finished renovation, Kiernan said, he wept. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="534" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820716?width=700&amp;height=534" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hammersmith Farm, in Newport, RI</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carol M. Highsmith/Buyenlarge/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “There are pretty houses in the Hamptons and in Nantucket, but we wanted to do something that was authentically connected to what had gone on here for a very long time,” Kiernan said.</p><p> Born into wealth, Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis lived in homes ranging from apartments in New York City to houses in Georgetown and estates in Newport, Virginia and Martha&#39;s Vineyard. Many were legacy properties that, nearly 30 years after Jackie&#39;s death, still command top-dollar among luxury buyers drawn to their classical style, history and aesthetic.</p><p> In Washington, DC, real-estate agent Jamie Peva of Washington Fine Properties said homes tied to Jackie and John Kennedy can command a roughly 10% premium even in Georgetown, a historic neighborhood full of notable residents. “It might be a conversation starter that [former Secretary of State Henry] Kissinger lived there, but it doesn&#39;t translate into money unless it&#39;s the Kennedys,” he said.<br><br> Peva said it helps that the couple—along with their families and later, Jackie herself—owned exceptional homes in prime locations. “The house they went to the White House from was one of the most important houses in Georgetown,” Peva said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="722" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818423?width=700&amp;height=722" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Kennedys, pictured in 1961, lived in Georgetown before moving to the White House.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Jackie&#39;s name is an instant draw and marketing boon, said Eileen O&#39;Neill of the Corcoran Group, who is marketing Lasata, one of her childhood homes in the Hamptons, for $55 million. But provenance only goes so far, O&#39;Neill said, and Lasata&#39;s classic elegance and exacting renovations by the recent owners have drawn interest from potential buyers. “Comparable sales and the climate of the market is really what dictates price,” she said.</p><p> That was the case when Jackie&#39;s childhood apartment at 740 Park Avenue in Manhattan sold for $25.25 million in 2017, said Jeremy Stein of Sotheby&#39;s International Realty, who was involved in the deal. The buyer was banking heir Jacob M. Safra, records show. “The building speaks for itself,” said Stein, citing location, architecture and a long history of prominent residents, including Jackie. “It remains this iconic, great building that has a cachet, but it lives up to the cachet,” he said.</p><p> Read on for a closer look at notable properties tied to Jackie over the years, based on property records, multiple biographies and the accounts of real-estate agents. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/0c296686-a760-4b9d-a314-09cc321612ca-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> As a young child, Jackie spent summers at a lavish East Hampton estate owned by her paternal grandfather, John Vernou Bouvier Jr. Known as Lasata, meaning “place of peace” in the Algonquin language of the native Montaukett people, the estate sat on roughly 14 acres. It was set back from Further Lane and had a long, curving drive and 15-room manor built in the 1910s, according to the book “Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis: A Life” by Donald Spoto. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="511" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818420?width=639&amp;height=511" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie, left, spent summers in East Hampton in homes owned by her grandparents.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> When designer Reed Krakoff and his wife, interior designer Delphine Krakoff, bought the property in 2007, the manor hadn&#39;t been renovated in years, Reed Krakoff said. The Krakoffs paid $25 million for two parcels totaling about 11 acres, records show. The couple spent nearly two years restoring the house, using building techniques and materials original to the home, he said. They restored single-pane glass windows and instead of sheetrock walls they used three-coat plaster on metal lathe. They also refurbished and restored all of the existing hardware and fixtures, he said. (For example, the bathtubs are porcelain over iron.)</p><p> Krakoff said there is a “mystique” to owning a famous property, but the real draw was the house itself. “It&#39;s a really rare thing to find a beautiful, historic house that hasn&#39;t been altered in a way that takes away from the authenticity,” he said. The couple, who have restored around 15 homes, uncovered and restored original oak-paneled walls from the Bouviers&#39; time under Louis XV-style paneling added later. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/019dae13-6292-447b-ba02-4bbb620702e5.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Around 2017, the Krakoffs subdivided the property and sold it in two parts. A neighbor purchased a nearly 4-acre parcel with a sunken tennis court for $11.25 million. David Zander, a television, commercial and film producer based in Los Angeles, paid $24 million in 2018 for a roughly 7.2-acre parcel comprising the main house, a swimming pool, pool house, guesthouse, caretaker&#39;s cottage and a garage with a workshop.</p><p> Zander said the scale, proportion and aesthetics of the home drew him in—not the Jackie connection. “If Jackie lived in a hovel would I be interested in buying it? No,” he said. But he admitted that over time, the connection became interesting. “Through a house, you become a small part of American history,” he said. Zander said he has repaired structural issues and made other improvements to the home, including adding a glass front door so that visitors can see through the house to the garden.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-os-childhood-hamptons-home-lists-for-55-million-8187989c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">The property</a> also has a visual easement in front to maintain a view of the house from the street. “It&#39;s a significant historical structure for all to enjoy,” Zander said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/da99f27d-8cc1-479d-a3b0-40bff490d707-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> When she wasn&#39;t at Lasata, Jackie and her parents summered at Wildmoor, a circa-1800s house in East Hampton owned by her paternal grandfather, who let his son and daughter-in-law stay there rent-free, according to multiple accounts. The house, located a few houses down from Grey Gardens, the famed estate once owned by Jackie&#39;s cousins, was a “charming old wooden-frame structure, clapboarded and shingled, with a widow&#39;s walk overlooking acres of potato fields, a cattail swamp, and the distant, roaring Atlantic,” according to John H. Davis&#39; 1993 book “The Kennedys: Dynasty and Disaster.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="909" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818419?width=700&amp;height=909" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie and her parents lived rent-free at Wildmoor, which was owned by her grandfather.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bettmann Archive/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Later, the abstract expressionist Adolph Gottlieb and his wife, Esther Gottlieb, purchased Wildmoor and turned a free-standing carriage house into an art studio. Around 1990, the attorney Richard D. Spizzirri purchased the property; his estate sold it for $6.8 million in 2021, records show. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/ac9e37b1-b5b9-4344-9f66-72586e6c854d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> David Tosher, a residential design consultant who advised the buyer, said the roughly 5,700-square-foot house with six bedrooms hadn&#39;t been renovated in decades. The wood on the bottom of the house was rotten from sitting in mud for decades and “the house was held there by the grace of God,” he said. The kitchen was “uneatable,” a glass atrium was leaking and at some point, portions of the elevator shaft were blocked off and removed, rendering it useless, he said. Tosher said workers took apart the house and rebuilt it entirely in a slightly different location farther from the road. They kept the original framing but added a full basement. They also used old photographs to restore original features including the main staircase, some doors and a gooseneck-curved railing. “We rebuilt everything but left the history,” Tosher said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/30ae4b25-5ebc-42d2-9413-17f5d1421fa2-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> As a child in the 1930s, Jackie lived with her parents at 740 Park Avenue, an elegant, limestone-clad building designed by Rosario Candela. The building was developed by Jackie&#39;s maternal grandfather, James T. Lee, who let his daughter, Janet Lee Bouvier, and son-in-law, John Vernou “Black Jack” Bouvier III, live there rent-free, according to multiple accounts.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Flamboyant but cash-strapped, Jackie&#39;s father gutted the kitchen and added gold-plated fixtures to the bathroom, according to Michael Gross&#39; “740 Park: The Story of the World&#39;s Richest Apartment Building.” But his finances were such that he couldn&#39;t afford to furnish it when he was done, leaving open space for Jackie and her sister to roller-skate through what became one of New York City&#39;s most iconic buildings, according to the book.</p><p> Today the apartment is owned by Jacob M. Safra, an heir to a banking fortune, who purchased it for $25.25 million in 2017, records show. The sellers, hedge funder David Ganek and his wife, Danielle Ganek, renovated the duplex and had it on the market for several years, asking as much as $44 million in 2014.</p><p> Stein of Sotheby&#39;s, who represented the seller, said the Kennedy and Bouvier cachet is real although the building itself is the main draw for most buyers. “The building speaks for itself,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/f82f3f77-7910-4471-a9fa-c600419fd530-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Jackie moved to Merrywood in the 1940s after her mother married Standard Oil heir Hugh D. Auchincloss Jr., according to Spoto&#39;s “A Life.” Located on the banks of the Potomac River, the estate is about 8 miles from downtown Washington with a Georgian-style house spanning more than 16,000 square feet.</p><p> By the 1960s, Auchincloss, facing financial constraints, agreed to sell Merrywood, then spanning about 46 acres, for $650,000 to real-estate developers and brothers Sheldon and Ira Magazine, according to Jan Pottker&#39;s 2002 book “Janet and Jackie: The Story of a Mother and Her Daughter, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.” The Magazine brothers&#39; plans to build 1,030 high-rise apartments on the site sparked “an enormous cry” among neighbors, the book said. After the deal went through in 1963, the Kennedy White House took steps to block the high-rise development. “Jackie sparked it,” said the book, citing her commitment to preservation and environmental causes. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="553" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818405?width=700&amp;height=553" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie lived at Merrywood, pictured in 1962, following her mother&#39;s marriage to owner Hugh D. Auchincloss Jr.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ASSOCIATED PRESS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In 1965, the Magazine brothers sold the entire property for $650,000 to real-estate developer C. Wyatt Dickerson and his then-wife, Nancy Dickerson, who retained the main residence and more than 7 acres and built about 46 smaller homes on the remaining land, according to “Janet and Jackie.” In 2005, AOL co-founder Steve Case bought the 7-acre original manor residence for a then-record sum of $24.5 million, records show. Thirteen years later, he sold it for $43 million to the Kingdom Saudi Arabia, the government of which expressed “tremendous respect” for the home&#39;s place in American history in a statement at the time.</p><p> Marc C. Lowham of TTR Sotheby&#39;s International Realty, who was involved in the 2018 deal, said the property&#39;s location and provenance made it one of the most timeless and valuable estates in the area. Many original details remain, including the basic floor plan and elaborate plaster moldings. The gated estate also has formal gardens, a swimming pool and tennis court. “The Jackie Kennedy legacy there still feels very much alive,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5880d3e8-cd01-470a-a46e-56bfd86537af-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In 1953, Jackie and John Kennedy&#39;s 1,200-person wedding reception took place at Hammersmith Farm, an estate overlooking Narragansett Bay in Newport, RI The Auchincloss family estate had gardens designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, according to “A Life.” During the summer of 1961, when the Kennedys visited Hammersmith, the farm was dubbed “the summer White House” by the press, according to “Janet and Jackie.”</p><p> The White House installed phones in the main house and the Coast Guard inspected all boats and ships sailing past, the book said. After the oil crisis of the 1970s, Jackie&#39;s mother, Janet Auchincloss, sold the main house and about 54 acres for about $825,000 and the property was turned into a museum, the book said.</p><p> When plans to rezone the property and build condos emerged in the 1990s, William F. Farley, a Rhode Island native and former CEO of Fruit of the Loom, swooped in and paid $6.675 million in 1997, records show. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818413?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie and John Kennedy&#39;s 1953 wedding reception took place at Hammersmith Farm, an Auchincloss-owned estate in Newport, RI</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sygma/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818410?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Kennedys, pictured in 1962, had an office at Hammersmith.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sygma/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “My motivation was really simple,” he said. “It was to make sure it wouldn&#39;t get developed and it would remain part of American history.” Farley kept it as a museum, and sold it a few years later to Kiernan on the condition that Hammersmith would never be developed commercially. Kiernan paid just over $8 million, records show.</p><p> Kiernan said there was work to be done. “No one had lived here for a quarter-century,” he said. The Kiernans reinforced the structure with steel and wood beams, replaced the roof and redid the plumbing and electrical. They removed parking lots and restored farmland, and today Hammersmith is a working farm with horses, llamas and other animals; an old tea house has been repurposed as an aviary for peacocks, Kiernan said.</p><p> Kiernan said the Auchincloss family was “incredibly gracious” and gave him a portrait of Kennedy that is hanging in his office—which he was told Kennedy also used. The Kiernans, who purchased some of the home&#39;s original furniture at auction, have since held reunions at Hammersmith, he said. Kiernan said when he was working on Wall Street, the farm was like a “tonic” that would calm him. Two of his daughters have gotten married there, and the family feels a sense of responsibility for it. “We&#39;re trustees of it more than anything,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/c35c58ed-3b19-46c9-a634-d14f37262157-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> About three years after getting married, Jackie and John Kennedy bought a house in Hyannis Port that became part of the famous Kennedy compound. The couple paid $45,948 for the shingled house, located next to homes owned by John Kennedy&#39;s parents, Rose and Joe Kennedy, and his brother Robert F. Kennedy&#39;s home, records show. Built around 1925, Jackie and John Kennedy&#39;s house has about 4,484 square feet of interior space and sits on about 0.81 acres, according to the Barnstable County assessor. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3d2181e5-f058-4467-aecf-86900af4d845.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Spanning about 6 acres of waterfront, the compound was a base for Kennedy&#39;s presidential campaign. After the 1960 election, “the grass in front of Jack&#39;s deck became the temporary stage for twice-daily press conferences for the next couple of weeks,” according to Kate Storey&#39;s book “White House By the Sea: A Century of the Kennedys at Hyannis Port.” It remained a summer White House and presidential retreat until Kennedy&#39;s assassination in 1963, according to the National Park Service.</p><p> In 2004, Jackie&#39;s daughter, Caroline Kennedy, and son-in-law, Edwin Schlossberg, sold the house for $3 million to a Kennedy family trust, records show.  It is currently used as a summer residence by Ted Kennedy Jr. and his wife, Katherine “Kiki” Kennedy, who remodeled the house and donated the original windows, cabinets and shingles to the John F. Kennedy Hyannis Museum, according to Wendy Northcross, the museum&#39;s executive director. The museum allowed local artists to repurpose the materials into artifacts and other works of art. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> The house is currently worth around $4.5 million, according to Zillow&#39;s “Zestimate.” In 2012, Rose and Joe Kennedy&#39;s home—known as the Big House—was donated to the Edward M. Kennedy Institute for the US Senate to be preserved. “This house was my family&#39;s epicenter,” Ted Kennedy Jr. said at the time. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/353f6970-acc1-491f-bed2-2a6632e698b3-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In 1957, before Kennedy&#39;s run for president, he and the future first lady bought their first house together, a red brick Federal-style building on N Street in Georgetown. “Kennedy paid $82,000 for it, and Jackie&#39;s remodeling cost another $18,000,” according to “A Life.” She filled the house with Louis XV armchairs and porcelains, Louis XVI dining chairs and an antique carpet. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/6df2da95-261d-4182-8d6b-21e5eb6afd0b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Following Kennedy&#39;s assassination in 1963, Jackie returned to Georgetown, where she bought a 1790s house that is currently listed on the National Register of Historic Places.</p><p> She paid about $175,000 for it, but moved to New York about a year later to escape the barrage of tourists that gathered outside, according to “A Life.” Yolande Betbeze Fox, a onetime Miss America, bought the house in 1976, records show. Construction entrepreneur David W. Hudgens purchased it for $5.25 million in 2017. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/86ad8303-f95c-4b8d-a0cf-faab53debfc2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Before buying Fox&#39;s house, Hudgens purchased two adjacent properties for $1.2 million and $1.625 million, records show. Once he owned the trio, he tapped architect Dale Overmyer to combine the properties into a mansion that is more than 15,300 square feet and has 13 bedrooms.</p><p> Overmyer said Hudgens had a passage built underneath the homes to connect them. Certain features of the former Kennedy home remain, including a wood-paneled library and dining room with gold leaf ceiling. The fireplaces—saved from a dumpster by Overmyer—are also original.</p><p> Following Hudgens&#39;s death in 2022, the assemblage of houses came on the market for $26.5 million this year. It is currently priced at $19.5 million, according to Zillow. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d9e069f1-5b2f-4564-92c0-54714ba10634-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Leaving Washington after Kennedy&#39;s death, Jackie purchased a 14-room apartment at 1040 Fifth Avenue, overlooking Central Park and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. “The arrangements for the apartment at 1040 Fifth were made so quietly that her name did not appear on the contract,” according to “Janet and Jackie,” which said she paid roughly $200,000 for the apartment, which spans the entire 15th floor. Jackie furnished the apartment with antique furniture and art, and lived there until her death in 1994, the book said.</p><p> The following year, the late billionaire David Koch purchased the apartment for $9.2 million, according to C. David Heymann&#39;s book “American Legacy: The Story of John and Caroline Kennedy,” published in 2008. “Mrs. Onassis was very conservative financially, and she didn&#39;t spend much on it,” Koch later told the Observer. “We gutted the apartment and redid everything.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="488" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818401?width=700&amp;height=488" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie, on Fifth Avenue in 1964, moved to New York to avoid publicity in Washington, DC</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>In 2006, Koch sold the apartment for $30 million to hedge funder Glenn Dubin and his wife, Eva Dubin, records show.</p><p> Although luxury buyers have more options than ever, including new condominiums, 1040 Fifth is still considered one of the city&#39;s best buildings, said Deborah Grubman of the Corcoran Group, who was involved in the 2006 sale. She said Jackie&#39;s celebrity status bolstered sales prices after she died—“She had some fake pearls that went for crazy numbers also,” Grubman said—but the building&#39;s attributes stand on their own. “Nobody did an apartment better than they did in those days,” she said. “The view is still something that&#39;s hard to duplicate.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1380" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/6d3a48b2-8040-4709-941e-f2a338e85920-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In 1978, Jackie bought over 300 acres of land on the tip of Martha&#39;s Vineyard where she built a secluded summer residence known as Red Gate Farm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818424?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jackie purchased more than 300 acres on Martha&#39;s Vineyard where she built a summer retreat.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brooks Kraft/Sygma/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> After paying just over $1 million for the land, Jackie tapped architect Hugh Newell Jacobsen to design the shingled Cape Cod saltbox-style main house and a two-story guesthouse, which cost about $3.1 million and was completed in 1981, according to “A Life.” Philanthropist and horticulturist Rachel “Bunny” Mellon, who designed the White House Rose Garden when Jackie was first lady, designed the landscapes.</p><p> Over the years, Jackie hosted President Bill Clinton and others at the home, but she also clashed with a group of the Wampanoag Native Americans, who claimed the right to access a beachfront area on her property. (She settled the dispute in 1990.)</p><p> After Jackie&#39;s death, her daughter, Caroline Kennedy, and son-in-law, Edwin Schlossberg, enlisted Deborah Berke, dean of the Yale School of Architecture, to head up a multimillion-dollar renovation of the property, which also includes a pool, a tennis court and a treehouse Jackie built for her grandchildren. Caroline Kennedy listed it for sale in 2019, asking $65 million. At the time, she said in a statement that her three children had grown and it was time for the family to “spread its wings.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          edgetoedge
"><figure class="media-object-image img-edgetoedge"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818505?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> She paid about $1 million for the land and built a house that was completed in 1981.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Christie&#39;s International Real Estate</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In 2020 and 2021, however, two conservation groups—the Martha&#39;s Vineyard Land Bank Commission and Sheriff&#39;s Meadow Foundation—bought the land in separate transactions totaling $37 million, the groups said. The family retained roughly 60 acres, including the residence.</p><p> “Many of these land conservation efforts take decades to achieve,” said Adam Moore, president of Sheriff&#39;s Meadow Foundation, who described the deal as “the pinnacle of my career in conservation.” The groups are currently seeking permits to open the property, now known as Squibnocket Pond Reservation, to the public. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><img width="600" height="1184" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b46c7859-e02b-424e-bc15-d0b3c7548cc6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> During the last decades of her life, Jackie retreated to a country home in New Jersey where she could ride horses. Located in Bernardsville, NJ, the property cost about $200,000 in 1974 and included a “two-story frame house on 10 acres of lush hunt country,” according to “A Life.” Jackie painted the outside yellow with white trim, the book said. “Inside, she furnished it with comfortable, chintz-covered country pieces.”</p><p> After she died, then-Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey said Jackie adopted Bernardsville “in pursuit of that elusive privacy” that she sought for much of her life. “There she indulged in her favorite pastime of horseback riding,” he said, in a memorial tribute shared with Congress.</p><p> In 1997, Caroline Kennedy and her brother, John F. Kennedy Jr., sold the property to their mother&#39;s former neighbor, Marjorie “Peggy” McDonnell Walsh for $1.475 million, records show.</p><p> “We tore down the house and built a new one,” Walsh said, declining to share details about the new house. “It doesn&#39;t matter,” she said. “The much more important thing is we both love the property. It&#39;s a private valley. It&#39;s beautiful.”</p><p> Write to EB Solomont at <a href="mailto:eb.solomont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eb.solomont@wsj.com</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Which of Jackie Kennedy&#39;s properties do you think is the most iconic?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-os-collection-of-homes-was-as-iconic-as-it-gets-2500daf4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/jackie-os-collection-of-homes-was-as-iconic-as-it-gets-2500daf4<author><![CDATA[E.B. Solomont]]></author><category>世家大厦</category><category>photo-research</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Home &amp; Garden</category><category> home &amp; garden</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pilobolus Review: The Dance-Theater Troupe’s ‘Big Five-Oh!’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该公司在乔伊斯剧院举行庆祝活动，数十年的演出组合展示了其标志性的运动精神和风格<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590099910144336830"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="1131" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820675?width=860&amp;height=1131" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 《歌谣》中的皮洛博洛斯</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：本·麦基翁</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590099910144336830"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">罗伯特·格雷斯科维奇</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 20 日下午 5:26 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pilobolus-review-the-dance-theater-troupes-big-five-oh-69dc2f93"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>目前，乔伊斯剧院 (Joyce Theatre) 的 Pilobolus 演出季为期三周，持续至 7 月 30 日，据称是为了庆祝其“五大哦！” (Big Five-Oh!)尽管这个舞蹈剧团成立于 1971 年，现在由 Renée Jaworski 和 Matt Kent 共同担任艺术总监。由于 Covid-19 大流行造成的中断，该团即将结束今年的黄金周年巡演。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p><strong>毛叶属</strong></p><p><em>乔伊斯剧院，截至 7 月 30 日</em></p></div></div><p>两套混合剧目（分别为节目 A 和 B，各有一次中场休息）组成了该剧团的 11 部作品，涵盖从剧团成立第一年到 2023 年创作的作品。 Pilobolus 因在放牧动物粪便中发现的一种活性真菌而得名，最初由三名男子组成，后来发展成为现在由四名男子和两名女子组成的长期核心团体，并有交替表演者。</p><p>在本赛季的两个节目中，这两个节目将在最后一周交替进行，B 呈现出更强的组合。它的第一部分以“无题”结束，这可能是该乐队最熟悉和最受欢迎的作品。</p><p>该剧由罗比·巴尼特 (Robby Barnett)、艾莉森·蔡斯 (Alison Chase)、玛莎·克拉克 (Martha Clarke)、摩西·彭德尔顿 (Moses Pendleton)、迈克尔·特雷西 (Michael Tracy) 和乔纳森·沃尔肯 (Jonathan Wolken) 于 1975 年创作并首演，可以说是该团体中最令人难忘的六重奏。时断时续的超现实活动中经常出现诙谐的动作和哑剧组合，唤起了维多利亚时代的氛围，促使剧院注意到“今晚的表演包含裸体”。模拟和实际的裸体有时都是 Pilobolus 剧目的一部分，但这些实例都不是淫荡的；一位记者很早就将这个团体的审美观比作裸泳。</p><p> 《论事物的本质》是 2014 年由 13 名合作者创作的作品，它以三位几乎裸体的表演者（纳撒尼尔·布赫斯鲍姆、昆西·埃利斯和马龙·费利兹）在我观看的表演中的简洁活动作为节目 B 的开头。他们大部分的慢动作发生在一个模型架上，一个孤独的女人和两个男人在维瓦尔第精选的伴奏下摆出雕塑般的姿势。他们的姿势表明埃德沃德·迈布里奇的定格动作照片研究与尼古拉斯·普桑的人物分组的融合。</p><p>节目 A 中的“Branches”（2017 年，由 10 名合作者完成）由 David Van Tiegham 进行声音设计，展示了当前的公司沐浴在 Thom Weaver 的金色灯光下，穿着 Liz Prince 的裸色服装。其动作和互动从腼腆和卡通化的行为转变为发光身体的画面，将表演者的体格转变为令人印象深刻的动植物图像。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多舞蹈评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/like-water-for-chocolate-review-an-overstuffed-ballet-5c74e2e5?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“就像巧克力的水”评论：一部臃肿的芭蕾舞剧</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 28 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-ballet-review-balanchine-and-beyond-d98f57a9?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">纽约市芭蕾舞团评论：巴兰钦及其他芭蕾舞团</a><span class="date">2023 年 5 月 9 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/martha-graham-dance-company-in-its-founders-shadow-781038c7?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">玛莎·格雷厄姆舞蹈团：在创始人的阴影下</a><span class="date">2023 年 4 月 26 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/agua-review-pina-bauschs-brazilian-dance-spectacle-5e020dee?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“Água”评论：皮娜·鲍什 (Pina Bausch) 的巴西舞蹈奇观</a><span class="date">2023 年 3 月 7 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>Program B 的“Walklyndon”（1971 年，作者为 Wolken、Lee Harris、Barnett 先生和 Pendleton 先生）是此处收录的最早的作品。整个剧团在舞台交叉处大步跨过舞台时的歌舞杂耍般的打闹碰撞和杂技般的相遇，在沉默中不断引起观众的笑声、咯咯笑声以及奇怪的呻吟声。另一首老歌《空虚的追求者的独奏》（1980 年，由特雷西先生为本·韦伯斯特的《甜蜜的乔治亚·布朗》录制）出现在 A 节目中，讲述了一个倒霉蛋布赫斯鲍姆先生，他是一个无声电影风格的小丑，他发现自己走在像浮冰一样不稳定的木管上。最终，他被困在一张两人座的长凳下，这让观众觉得很有趣。</p><p>这些节目包括三场纽约首映； A 上有两个，B 上有一个。没有一个很突出。</p><p> A 节目的《晚间之歌》由现任公司及其艺术总监创作，配乐由 Jad Abumrad 创作，服装由 Valerie St. Pierre Smith 设计，其中包括对大长度扎染织物的操纵，以不同的方式塑造汉娜·克林克曼 (Hannah Klinkman) 和费利斯女士 (Feliz) 的形象，她们穿着休闲的鲜艳色彩。德里昂·洛曼、扎克·维斯、</p>埃利斯先生和布赫斯鲍姆先生的穿着有点像角斗士，行为举止也像女木偶师。<p></p><p> 《民谣》是节目 A 的另一部纽约首映剧，有一种讲座的感觉。沙格蒂科克部落民族的达琳·卡斯卡克 (Darlene Kascak) 获得了讲故事的荣誉，她提供了关于虐待土著儿童的画外音。尽管以费利兹女士为中心人物的四人组进行了集体动作，伴随着本·索利的音景和雅尼克·戈茨的道具，这首“民谣”仍然更多地是在背诵故事，而不是体现故事。</p><p> 《唤醒心》是节目 B 的纽约首映式，也是其最弱的作品，它重复使用了可识别的皮洛博鲁斯结构的升降机和身体结，其效果只不过是传递效果。</p><p> 7 月 28 日，本赛季的最后一周将迎来“五巨头”的第 100 次交战。旅游。 Pilobolus 在董事会任职已有半个世纪，即使是不太引人注目的努力也帮助 Pilobolus 维持了其受欢迎程度，并为其未来提供了动力。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。格雷斯科维奇为《华尔街日报》撰写有关舞蹈的文章。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 21:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pilobolus-review-the-dance-theater-troupes-big- Five-oh-69dc2f93</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pilobolus-review-the-dance-theater-troupes-big- Five-oh-69dc2f93<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>舞蹈/芭蕾舞</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>剧院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>舞蹈</category><category>芭蕾舞</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>剧院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item></channel></rss>